1 Introduction

1.1 Background

Under the fmnist folder in data_input directory, the folder contains train and test set of 10 different categories for 28 x 28 pixel sized fashion images, use the following glossary for your target labels:

categories <- c(T-shirt, Trouser, Pullover, Dress, Coat, Sandal, Shirt, Sneaker, Bag, Boot)

Tasks to be performed

Data preparation.

Design neural network layer design for input, hidden, output layer, and activation functions.

Demonstrate cross validation method and model evaluation.

1.2 Data Source

Dataset of 60,000 28x28 grayscale images of 10 fashion(clothes) categories, along with a test set of 10,000 images. You can learn more on Wikipedia:

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MNIST_database

1.2.1 Overview of Label

Label Description

0 T-shirt/top

1 Trouser

2 Pullover

3 Dress

4 Coat

5 Sandal

6 Shirt

7 Sneaker

8 Bag

9 Ankle boot

2 Preprocessing

2.1 Data Table

library(data.table)
fmnist_train <- fread("data_input/fmnist/train.csv")
fmnist_test <- fread("data_input/fmnist/test.csv")

2.2 Transform Train/Test data into a matrix

# Turn the data frames into matrices
ftrain <- data.matrix(fmnist_train)
ftest <- data.matrix(fmnist_test)

# Strip the dimnames of ntrain and ntest.
dimnames(ftrain) <- NULL
dimnames(ftest) <- NULL

2.3 Setting up Train/Test Data and Labels

# Separate the labels from the train sets.
ftrain_data <- ftrain[, -1]
ftrain_label <- ftrain[, 1]

# This time we do it for the test set as well
ftest_data <- ftest[, -1]
ftest_label <- ftest[, 1]



# Use One-hot-encoding on the labels via the to_categorical() function.
ftrain_label_hot <- to_categorical(ftrain_label, 10)
ftest_label_hot <- to_categorical(ftest_label, 10)

2.4 Rescale all data

# Rescale all data from 0:255 into 0:1
ftrain_data <- ftrain_data/255
ftest_data <- ftest_data/255

2.5 Functions to enable the display of images

2.5.1 Function to plot results

# The "plotResults" function will print the image, but this time it will display the predicted result on the left of the image in white. 
# This is just a tool to help us check if our prediction was accurate.
plotResults <- function(images, preds) {
    
    x <- ceiling(sqrt(length(images)))
    par(mfrow = c(x, x), mar = c(0.1, 0.1, 0.1, 0.1))
    
    for (i in images) {
        m <- matrix(ftest_data[i, ], nrow = 28, byrow = TRUE)
        m <- apply(m, 2, rev)
        image(t(m), col = grey.colors(255), axes = FALSE)
        text(0.05, 0.1, col = "white", cex = 1.2, preds[i])
    }
    
}

3.1 Step 1: Define the model

# apply layers using layer_dense()
modelf <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 128, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(784)) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = 64, activation = "relu") %>%
  layer_dense(units = 10, activation = "softmax")

4 Neural Network Model - Final

4.1 Step 1: Define the model

library(keras)
input_shape <- c(28,28,1) 
modelfinal <- keras_model_sequential()
modelfinal %>%
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 32, kernel_size = c(5,5), activation = 'relu',
                input_shape = input_shape) %>%
  layer_conv_2d(filters = 64, kernel_size = c(3,3), activation = 'relu') %>%
  layer_max_pooling_2d(pool_size = c(2, 2)) %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.25) %>%
  layer_flatten() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu') %>%
  layer_dropout(rate = 0.5) %>%
  layer_dense(units = 10, activation = 'softmax')

4.2 Step 2: Compile the model

modelfinal %>% compile(
  loss = loss_categorical_crossentropy,     # https://keras.io/optimizers/
  optimizer = optimizer_adam(),    # https://arxiv.org/pdf/1212.5701.pdf
  metrics = c('accuracy')
)

4.3 Step 3: Train the model

dim(ftrain_data) <- c(nrow(ftrain_data), 28, 28, 1) 
dim(ftest_data) <- c(nrow(ftest_data), 28, 28, 1)

historyfinal <- modelfinal %>% 
  fit(x = ftrain_data,
      y = ftrain_label_hot,
      epoch = 13, 
      batch_size = 128,
      validation_data = list(ftest_data, ftest_label_hot))

plot(historyfinal)

4.4 Step 4: Evaluate the model

evafinal <- modelfinal %>% 
  evaluate(ftest_data, ftest_label_hot)

# Save all the probabilities of the prediction produced at the output layer into probfinal.
probfinal <- modelfinal %>% 
  predict_proba(ftest_data)

# Save all the predicted classes into predfinal.
predfinal <- modelfinal %>% 
  predict_classes(ftest_data)
# Predict the results when the test set is passed into our trained NN.
prediction_test_final <- predict_classes(object = modelfinal, x =  ftest_data)

# Print the first 10 prediction results.
prediction_test_final[1:10]
##  [1] 0 1 2 6 3 6 8 6 5 0
#categories <- c("T-shirt", "Trouser", "Pullover", "Dress", "Coat", "Sandal", "Shirt", "Sneaker", "Bag", "Boot")
predfinal <- factor(predfinal, labels=categories)
finaltest_label <- factor(finaltest_label, labels=categories)  
cat('Test loss:', evafinal[[1]], '\n')
## Test loss: 0.2071187
cat('Test accuracy:', evafinal[[2]], '\n')
## Test accuracy: 0.9239

5 Summary

In the second Neural Network model, we look into tuning the dropout rate for regularization in an effort to limit overfitting and improve the models ability to generalize. To improve the performance, we also reduce the number of epochs from 30 to 13 and implement convolution and pooling layers into the model[^1].

Overall, the accuracy (0.9239) and loss (0.207) for the Test of 2nd Neural Network Model is better than accuracy(0.8962) and loss(0.3455) of the first Neural Network Model. The overall performance for Sensitivity, Specificity, Pos Pred Value and Neg Pred Value for the second NN model is generally higher than the first NN model .
